SIMPLE: patronize
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Patronize
<hw>Pa"tron*ize</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Patronized</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Patronizing</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>To act as patron toward; to support; to countenance; to favor; to
aid.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The idea has been <qex>patronized</qex> by two States only.</q>
<rj><qau>A. Hamilton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To trade with customarily; to frequent as a
customer.</def> <mark>[Commercial Cant]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To assume the air of a patron, or of a superior and
protector, toward; -- used in an unfavorable sense; <as>as, to
<ex>patronize</ex> one's equals</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Patronizer</ent>⟦br⟧
